jrg@aero.org writes:

>Gary Breckenridge writes
>> Don't go Clipper *OR* "Zipper"! I say, we MUST go grassroots public key 
>> with NO centralized "key escrows" or we're all SUNK!
>> 
>> Forget chips--all we need is software--and THAT is something we already 
>> have, we already know it is good, strong, and reliable. That's IT!
>> 
>> Michael Breckenridge
>> Journalist, Stars Media

>I hate to rain on your parade Michael, but software encryption is no  
>stronger than the operating system that your program resides on.  UNIX has  
>notoriously weak security.  Hardware encryption, at least if used  
>properly, adds a layer between your system and the outside world that must  
>be bypassed before damage can be done.

>In any case "Clipper" is a voice encryption chip.  To do voice encryption  
>in software requires considerable processing power.  This means a high  
>horsepower machine, since non-real-time voice encryption doesn't make  
>sense.  We're talking money here, more than the cost of Clipper.  If you  
>happen to have a machine with a powerful Floating Point DSP, A/D, and D/A  
>converters sitting on your desk your idea might work, but it won't be  
>cheap.

Hey! They have those things (floating point DSP, A/D, and D/A) in radar
detectors these days, not to mention built into some computer motherboards.

